⊢ quality-assessment
  given §r16-programs
  given corpus→feature-usage ≡ [... 30 entries ...]
  yield tier-list[], quality-issues[]

  -- ∴ EVALUATION:

  yield tier-list[] ≡ [
    { id: 1,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Full-stack demonstration of ⊢∘ + ⊢⊢ + oracle convergence with a concrete research domain; spawner template pattern is reusable." },
    { id: 2,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Cleanest § quotation usage — §summarize is rewritten while given/yield freeze; the self-improvement loop is the canonical ⊢∘ use case." },
    { id: 3,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Demonstrates substrate transfer (⊢ → ⊢=) as a runtime operation with oracle-gated verification; crystallization is Cell's unique capability." },
    { id: 4,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Recursive edge case discovery with ⊢⊢ spawner is genuinely novel; deeper-edges field enables multi-level test discovery." },
    { id: 5,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Meta-level: a Cell program that designs Cell programs. Uses § quotation for program-as-data. Trace-readiness cell simulates eval-one scheduling." },
    { id: 6,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Attacker-defender-judge triad is crisp and reusable; hardening Cell's own oracle spec section is an inspired domain choice." },
    { id: 7,  tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Good debate structure but the ⊢∘ multi-target evolution (both argue-for and argue-against) is underspecified — how does ⊢∘ handle two target cells?" },
    { id: 8,  tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Artifact accumulation pattern is unique — regression tests from ⊢⊢ become permanent, preventing regression. The adversarial loop ACCUMULATES, not just converges." },
    { id: 9,  tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "4 parallel ⊢∘ loops sharing one mediator is ambitious but spec-ambiguous — ⊢∘ semantics with multiple concurrent evolution targets is undefined." },
    { id: 10, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Socratic method maps perfectly to Cell's ⊢∘ loop; simulated student with calibrated misconceptions is realistic; ⊢⊢ remedial spawning is well-motivated." },
    { id: 11, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Impressive fractal structure with 4 spawner levels, but no ⊢∘ loop — relies entirely on ⊢⊢ + validation. The program would be enormous when fully spawned (potentially 60+ cells)." },
    { id: 12, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Solid recursive decomposition pattern but the ⊢∘ target (extract-implicit) is odd — it evolves the implicit extractor rather than the decomposer." },
    { id: 13, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Only program to use ⊥ as a genuine stop signal; oracle-terminated recursion is a distinct pattern from ⊢∘ max-iteration bounds." },
    { id: 14, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Good recursive graph building but sub-module analysis is somewhat forced — it decomposes ALL modules even when some are atomic." },
    { id: 15, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Comprehension oracle is charming ('would a 10-year-old understand?') but the recursive spawning for sub-explanations may not converge well." },
    { id: 16, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "⊢∘ as genetic algorithm is a creative mapping but the crossover/mutation operations are entirely in ∴ prose — no structural support from Cell syntax." },
    { id: 17, tier: "PROBLEMATIC",  justification: "Circular dependencies (geography↔history↔culture) violate Kahn's algorithm — these cells can NEVER become ready under eval-one. The program cannot execute as written." },
    { id: 18, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Multi-level spawning (acts→scenes→beats) is structurally sound but the bottom-up assembly (beat→scene→story) has underspecified dataflow for matching beats to their parent scenes." },
    { id: 19, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Canonical proof-carrying computation: LLM generates code, crystallized ⊢= verifier checks proof structure. The P-vs-NP split is Cell's killer feature." },
    { id: 20, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Uses ⊢∘ refine (not evolve) — naming inconsistency with the spec. The DSL design domain is a good fit but the critique scoring formula is overly prescriptive." },
    { id: 21, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Back-translation verification is a strong oracle strategy but the segment-level retranslation creates complexity that could lead to inconsistency." },
    { id: 22, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Per-claim fact-checkers via ⊢⊢ spawner are a natural fit; the fact-check → rewrite → re-check loop demonstrates oracle-gated convergence at fine granularity." },
    { id: 23, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Best demonstration of parallel oracles with a crystallized aggregator. The 5-oracle gauntlet (structural, semantic, factual, stylistic, logical) is thorough and reusable." },
    { id: 24, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Proof-carrying code with gap-filling evolution loop. The ⊢= verify-proof cell is the cleanest crystallized verifier in the corpus." },
    { id: 25, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Oracle chain decomposition from vague root to crystallized leaves is a unique and powerful pattern — transforms soft oracles into hard checks." },
    { id: 26, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Metacircular execution trace is the most Cell-like program in the corpus — cell-zero evaluating a Cell program, with the trace itself being a Cell document." },
    { id: 27, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Self-optimization concept is strong but the ⊢= compare cell's semantics-preserved check is actually semantic, not deterministic — it claims crystallization it doesn't have." },
    { id: 28, tier: "ADEQUATE",     justification: "Program algebra proof is theoretically elegant but heavy — 14 cells, mostly ⊢=, and the dual-program setup is verbose. The proof functions (missing-from, proof-covers) are pseudo-code." },
    { id: 29, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Zero-start bootstrap is the purest test of Cell's self-bootstrapping property. Two-phase spawning (specialists then gap-fillers) demonstrates monotonic growth." },
    { id: 30, tier: "EXEMPLARY",    justification: "Cell evolving its own spec is maximally meta. The awkward-program fragment is a concrete, falsifiable demonstration of the conditional dispatch gap." }
  ]

  yield quality-issues[] ≡ [
    "Program 17: CIRCULAR DEPENDENCIES — cannot execute under eval-one. The geography/history/culture cells form a cycle. This is the only structurally broken program in the corpus.",
    "Program 27: FALSE CRYSTALLIZATION — the compare cell is marked ▸ crystallized but its ⊢= body requires semantic judgment (determining if outputs are 'equivalent').",
    "Program 28: PSEUDO-CODE IN ⊢= — functions like proof-covers(), missing-from(), has-loop-invariant() are not real deterministic expressions. They look crystallized but would need LLM interpretation.",
    "Program 9: UNDEFINED SEMANTICS — 4 parallel ⊢∘ loops sharing one mediator. The spec defines ⊢∘ for single-target evolution. Multi-target concurrent evolution is not specified.",
    "Program 7: AMBIGUOUS ⊢∘ — evolve(argue-for, argue-against) takes two targets. The spec shows ⊢∘ evolve(cell) with one target.",
    "Programs 1,4,8,11,14: GLOB PATTERN DEPENDENCY — 'given cell-*→field' is used extensively but not defined in the spec."
  ]

  -- ORACLE CHECKS:
  ⊨ tier-list has 30 entries ✓
  ⊨ each entry has a tier and justification ✓
  ⊨ at least 1 program is rated PROBLEMATIC ✓ (program 17)

  -- DECISION: all oracles pass → FREEZE quality-assessment

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- STATE AFTER FRAME 3: corpus + pattern-analysis + quality-assessment frozen
-- Ready set: { spec-gaps }
--   spec-gaps: corpus→feature-usage ✓, pattern-analysis→anti-patterns ✓
-- Blocked: { synthesis (needs spec-gaps→gaps ✗, spec-gaps→proposals ✗) }
