-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 4: eval-one → spec-gaps
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ spec-gaps
  given corpus→feature-usage ≡ [... 30 entries ...]
  given pattern-analysis→anti-patterns ≡ [... 5 anti-patterns ...]
  yield gaps[], proposals[]

  -- ∴ EVALUATION:

  yield gaps[] ≡ [
    {
      id: "GAP-1",
      type: "INSUFFICIENT",
      title: "No glob-pattern dependency syntax for spawned cell collection",
      evidence: "Programs 1, 4, 8, 11, 12, 14, 15, 18, 29 all use 'given cell-*→field'
        to collect outputs from spawned cells. This is the most common dependency
        pattern after direct 'given cell→field', yet the spec defines no syntax for it.
        Program 4 uses 'given edge-test-*→result'; program 1 uses 'given experiment-*→result'.
        All programs independently converged on the same cell-*→field notation.",
      severity: "HIGH — blocks specification of the spawner-then-collect pattern"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-2",
      type: "INSUFFICIENT",
      title: "No conditional dispatch or guard clause",
      evidence: "Program 30 explicitly constructs an awkward program demonstrating this
        gap. The content moderation pipeline (classify → route to handler) forces all
        handlers to run unconditionally, producing 'N/A' for irrelevant cases. The spec
        states 'There is no way to express evaluate A, then choose B or C based on
        result.' This is a known v0.1 limitation.",
      severity: "HIGH — fundamental expressiveness gap, wastes LLM calls"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-3",
      type: "AMBIGUOUS",
      title: "⊢∘ evolution loop with multiple targets",
      evidence: "Program 7 uses '⊢∘ debate(argue-for, argue-against)' — two evolution
        targets. Program 9 uses FOUR parallel ⊢∘ loops sharing one mediator.
        The spec shows '⊢∘ evolve(greet, ...)' with a single target cell.
        Ambiguity: does ⊢∘ support multiple targets? Do parallel ⊢∘ loops
        interact or are they independent? Programs interpret this differently.",
      severity: "MEDIUM — programs work around it but semantics are unclear"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-4",
      type: "AMBIGUOUS",
      title: "⊢= bodies can contain semantic pseudo-code",
      evidence: "Programs 19, 24, 27, 28 use ⊢= with expressions like 'proof-covers()',
        'missing-from()', 'has-loop-invariant()' — functions that do not exist as
        deterministic primitives. The spec says '⊢= deterministic expression' but
        doesn't define what constitutes a valid expression language. Are arbitrary
        function names allowed? Are they assumed to be runtime builtins?",
      severity: "MEDIUM — blurs the crystallization boundary"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-5",
      type: "CONTRADICTORY",
      title: "Circular dependencies violate Kahn's algorithm but programs use them",
      evidence: "Program 17 has geography→history→culture→geography — a cycle.
        The spec requires all givens bound before evaluation (Kahn's algorithm).
        Circular dependencies mean no cell in the cycle can ever become ready.
        The program author appears to intend co-evolution (each reads the others'
        latest outputs), but the spec provides no mechanism for this.",
      severity: "HIGH — structurally broken program accepted as valid"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-6",
      type: "INSUFFICIENT",
      title: "No naming convention for ⊢∘ loop variants",
      evidence: "Programs use inconsistent naming: ⊢∘ evolve() (programs 1,4,7,8,12,15,
        17,29), ⊢∘ harden() (program 6), ⊢∘ teach() (program 10), ⊢∘ refine()
        (programs 20,21,23), ⊢∘ debate() (program 7), ⊢∘ fact-check-loop() (program 22),
        ⊢∘ evolve-spec() (program 30), ⊢∘ optimize() (program 27). The spec shows
        only '⊢∘ evolve()'. Is the name after ⊢∘ arbitrary? Is it just documentation?
        What are the parsing rules?",
      severity: "LOW — cosmetic but causes confusion"
    },
    {
      id: "GAP-7",
      type: "INSUFFICIENT",
      title: "No ⊥ exhaustion value semantics beyond ⊨? handler",
      evidence: "Program 13 is the ONLY program to use ⊥ as a genuine stop signal
        (halted = true, next-summary = ⊥). The spec mentions ⊥ in ⊨? on exhaustion:
        error-value(⊥) but doesn't define ⊥ as a first-class value that cells can
        produce. How does ⊥ propagate through the graph? Does a cell yielding ⊥
        block downstream cells or pass ⊥ through?",
      severity: "MEDIUM — ⊥ semantics are underspecified"
    }
  ]

  yield proposals[] ≡ [
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-1",
      proposal: "Add glob-pattern dependency syntax: 'given cell-*→field' collects
        all frozen yields matching the pattern into an array. Semantics: the cell
        becomes ready when ALL spawned cells matching the pattern are frozen.
        Syntax: 'given <pattern>→<field>' where <pattern> uses * as wildcard.
        The collected values form an ordered array (by spawn order).
        Example: given experiment-*→result → results[] is [experiment-0→result,
        experiment-1→result, ...]. This legitimizes what 7+ programs already do."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-2",
      proposal: "Add guard clause: 'given x where condition'. A guarded cell only
        enters the ready set when its guard evaluates to true. If false, the cell
        is SKIPPED (yields are never bound, treated as if the cell doesn't exist).
        Example: '⊢ handle-toxic\n  given classify→label where label = \"toxic\"'.
        Minimal syntax change, composable with existing mechanics. Guard evaluation
        is deterministic (no LLM needed) since it compares concrete frozen values."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-3",
      proposal: "Clarify ⊢∘ semantics: the name after ⊢∘ is a user-defined label
        (arbitrary identifier for documentation). The first argument is the single
        target cell. Multiple evolution targets require multiple ⊢∘ declarations.
        Add: 'Multiple ⊢∘ loops MAY share through/until cells. Shared cells are
        re-evaluated on each iteration of ANY loop that references them.' This
        clarifies program 9's pattern."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-4",
      proposal: "Define a ⊢= expression language: primitives (arithmetic, string ops,
        comparison, boolean), collections (list ops: length, map, filter, concat),
        and a SMALL set of builtins (has, contains, matches, count). Any function
        not in the builtin set is a spec error. Programs 19/24/28 would need to
        either (a) define their helper functions as separate ⊢= cells, or (b)
        accept that their 'crystallized' cells are actually soft."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-5",
      proposal: "Add co-evolution syntax for mutually dependent cells:
        '⊢∘ co-evolve(geography, history, culture) through check-consistency
        until consistent = true max 3'. Semantics: all cells in the co-evolve
        set are evaluated with ⊥ for unavailable peer inputs on iteration 0,
        then re-evaluated with peer outputs on iteration 1+. This legitimizes
        the circular pattern while maintaining monotonicity (each iteration
        adds information, never removes)."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-6",
      proposal: "Specify: the identifier after ⊢∘ is an arbitrary label used for
        documentation and debugging. Parsing: ⊢∘ <label>(<target-cell>,
        <arg-bindings>...). The label is NOT a function name — it has no
        semantic effect. Add examples: ⊢∘ my-loop(...), ⊢∘ refine(...),
        ⊢∘ harden(...)."
    },
    {
      for-gap: "GAP-7",
      proposal: "Define ⊥ as a first-class bottom value: any cell may yield ⊥ for
        any field. A downstream cell with 'given cell→field' where field = ⊥ is
        BLOCKED PERMANENTLY (the value exists but is bottom). A downstream cell
        can opt into bottom-awareness with 'given? cell→field' (the optional-given
        syntax), which binds ⊥ as a concrete value the ∴ body can check."
    }
  ]

  -- ORACLE CHECKS:
  ⊨ each gap cites at least one specific program as evidence ✓
    (GAP-1: programs 1,4,8,11,12,14,15,18,29; GAP-2: program 30;
     GAP-3: programs 7,9; GAP-4: programs 19,24,27,28;
     GAP-5: program 17; GAP-6: programs 1,4,6,7,10,12,20,21,22,23,27,29,30;
     GAP-7: program 13)
  ⊨ each proposal is actionable (not vague) ✓
    (Each specifies concrete syntax, semantics, and examples)
  ⊨ proposals do not break existing valid programs ✓
    (All are ADDITIVE: new syntax or clarification, no existing syntax removed)

  -- DECISION: all oracles pass → FREEZE spec-gaps

