-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- FRAME 5: eval-one → synthesis
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ synthesis
  given pattern-analysis→patterns ≡ [... 7 patterns ...]
  given pattern-analysis→anti-patterns ≡ [... 5 anti-patterns ...]
  given spec-gaps→gaps ≡ [... 7 gaps ...]
  given spec-gaps→proposals ≡ [... 7 proposals ...]
  given quality-assessment→tier-list ≡ [... 30 entries ...]
  yield findings, spec-recommendations[], next-steps[]

  -- ∴ EVALUATION:

  yield findings ≡ "
    TOP FINDINGS FROM THE R16 CORPUS

    1. ORACLE-GATED EVOLUTION IS CELL'S DOMINANT PATTERN.
       23 of 30 programs use ⊢∘ with a quality/convergence oracle as the loop
       termination condition. This is not one pattern among many — it IS what
       Cell programs look like. The generate → evaluate → refine → loop cycle
       appears in every category. The quality oracle (score ≥ N, boolean flag,
       convergence detection) is the universal gate. Programs 2 (prompt improvement),
       6 (spec hardening), 19 (code generation), and 25 (oracle chain) demonstrate
       the pattern most cleanly. Implication: ⊢∘ is not an advanced feature — it
       is Cell's primary control flow construct. The spec should treat it as such.

    2. SPAWNER-THEN-COLLECT IS THE SECOND CRITICAL PATTERN, AND IT'S UNSPECIFIED.
       15 of 30 programs use ⊢⊢ followed by a collector cell with glob-pattern
       dependencies (cell-*→field). This is the most important syntax gap in v0.1.
       Programs 1, 4, 8, 11, 22, 29 all independently converged on identical
       notation. The pattern is: decompose problem → ⊢⊢ spawn N cells from template →
       collector reads all N results → synthesize. Without glob-pattern dependencies,
       spawning is useless because there's no way to read the spawned outputs.

    3. THE ATTACKER-DEFENDER-JUDGE TRIAD IS CELL'S MOST REUSABLE ARCHITECTURE.
       Programs 6, 7, 8, 10, 30 all implement this three-role pattern. It maps
       perfectly to Cell because: (a) the attacker and defender are soft cells
       (∴ bodies change via ⊢∘), (b) the judge is often crystallizable (boolean
       verdict), (c) the ⊢∘ until clause naturally terminates when the attacker
       finds nothing. This is Cell's equivalent of a design pattern — it should be
       documented in the spec as an idiom.

    4. FALSE CRYSTALLIZATION IS A REAL RISK.
       Programs 27 and 28 mark cells as ⊢= (crystallized) when their bodies
       contain semantic operations masquerading as deterministic expressions.
       'proof-covers(proof-sketch, [\"found-case\", ...])' looks like a function
       call but requires LLM judgment to evaluate. The spec does not define what
       constitutes a valid ⊢= expression, leaving authors free to write semantic
       content in crystallized form. This erodes the trust boundary between soft
       and hard cells — the fundamental invariant Cell depends on.

    5. THE SPEC'S BIGGEST STRUCTURAL OMISSION: CONDITIONAL DISPATCH.
       Program 30 identifies and demonstrates this gap. Any program that classifies
       then routes (moderation, triage, error handling) hits the 'run all branches,
       output N/A for irrelevant ones' anti-pattern. This wastes LLM calls and adds
       boilerplate. A guard clause ('given x where condition') is the minimal fix that
       preserves Cell's existing mechanics while adding conditional execution. 0 of 30
       programs found a clean workaround — the gap is fundamental.
  "

  yield spec-recommendations[] ≡ [
    {
      priority: 1,
      title: "Add glob-pattern dependency syntax",
      rationale: "Blocks 15/30 programs from being spec-compliant. The spawner-then-collect
        pattern is Cell's second most common idiom. Without it, ⊢⊢ is half-complete.",
      proposal: "Syntax: 'given <pattern>→<field>' where <pattern> uses * wildcard.
        Semantics: collects all matching frozen yields into an ordered array.
        Cell becomes ready when all matching cells are frozen.",
      affected: "Programs 1, 4, 8, 11, 12, 14, 15, 18, 22, 29 (10 programs directly)"
    },
    {
      priority: 2,
      title: "Add guard clause for conditional dispatch",
      rationale: "Fundamental expressiveness gap demonstrated by program 30. Any
        classification/routing pattern is awkward without it. Wastes LLM calls.",
      proposal: "Syntax: 'given x where condition'. Cell only enters ready set if
        guard evaluates true on frozen values. Deterministic evaluation only.",
      affected: "Program 30 directly; would enable cleaner patterns in 7, 9, 17"
    },
    {
      priority: 3,
      title: "Define the ⊢= expression language",
      rationale: "False crystallization (programs 27, 28) erodes the soft/hard trust
        boundary. Without a defined expression language, ⊢= is meaningless.",
      proposal: "Enumerate valid ⊢= primitives: arithmetic, comparison, boolean,
        string ops, list ops (length, map, filter, concat), and a small builtin set.
        Anything outside this set is a spec error.",
      affected: "Programs 19, 24, 27, 28 would need revision"
    },
    {
      priority: 4,
      title: "Clarify ⊢∘ multi-target and naming semantics",
      rationale: "Programs 7 and 9 interpret ⊢∘ differently from the spec's single
        example. The naming (evolve, harden, refine, teach) is inconsistent.",
      proposal: "Specify: label is arbitrary, single target cell, multiple ⊢∘ loops
        may share through/until cells. Document the interaction semantics.",
      affected: "Programs 7, 9, 20, 21, 22, 23, 27, 30"
    },
    {
      priority: 5,
      title: "Add co-evolution syntax for mutually dependent cells",
      rationale: "Program 17 has circular dependencies that break Kahn's algorithm.
        Co-evolving cells (each reading the other's latest output) is a legitimate
        pattern that needs spec support, not a workaround.",
      proposal: "Syntax: ⊢∘ co-evolve(cell-a, cell-b, cell-c) with iterative
        evaluation (⊥ for unavailable peer inputs on first pass).",
      affected: "Program 17 directly; enables world-building and collaborative patterns"
    },
    {
      priority: 6,
      title: "Define ⊥ propagation semantics",
      rationale: "Only program 13 uses ⊥, suggesting it's underspecified. ⊥ as a
        stop signal, error value, and propagation marker needs clear rules.",
      proposal: "⊥ is a first-class value. Downstream cells with 'given cell→field'
        are blocked if field = ⊥. Optional given ('given? cell→field') allows
        ⊥-aware cells to proceed.",
      affected: "Program 13 directly; enables cleaner error handling in all programs"
    }
  ]

  yield next-steps[] ≡ [
    "R17: SPEC v0.2 DRAFT — Incorporate the top 3 recommendations (glob patterns,
     guard clauses, ⊢= expression language) into a v0.2 spec draft. Write 5 programs
     that exercise the new syntax to validate it works.",
    "R17: REWRITE PROBLEMATIC PROGRAMS — Program 17 needs either circular deps
     removed or co-evolution syntax. Programs 27/28 need false crystallization fixed.
     These are the acid test for spec changes.",
    "R17: IDIOM CATALOG — Document the 7 patterns identified here (attacker-defender-
     judge, spawner-then-collect, oracle-gated evolution, proof-carrying, §-quotation
     self-modification, staged pipeline, multi-perspective generation) as a Cell
     Idiom Catalog. Include the canonical program for each.",
    "R17: CONDITIONAL DISPATCH EVALUATION — Run program 30's proposed guard clause
     syntax through 3+ LLM agents to test comprehension. Does 'given x where
     condition' confuse agents? Is there a simpler alternative?",
    "R17: ⊢= EXPRESSION LANGUAGE RFC — Design and test the deterministic expression
     language. This is the crystallization boundary — getting it wrong means Cell
     loses its fundamental soft/hard invariant."
  ]

  -- ORACLE CHECKS:
  ⊨ findings contains at least 3 concrete insights ✓ (5 findings, each with specific program citations)
  ⊨ spec-recommendations are ordered by priority ✓ (priority 1 through 6)
  ⊨ next-steps are actionable ✓ (each specifies a concrete deliverable for R17)
  ⊨ every claim cites a specific program number ✓
    (Finding 1: programs 2,6,19,25; Finding 2: programs 1,4,8,11,22,29;
     Finding 3: programs 6,7,8,10,30; Finding 4: programs 27,28;
     Finding 5: program 30)

  -- DECISION: all oracles pass → FREEZE synthesis

